segments.text: That's good.
What Ray's salary was when he came?
Yeah, how much was he making when he came here in 1925?
Right here, you mean about the college people were a little bit standoffish about the Brian.
And of course, it has its roots in this, that Brian was business.
And business was commercial.
And business was making money perfectly properly.
And I don't know that I was ever
gouged in any sales or anything like that or not treated nicely or so on.
I think we came here at 2,400.
Yes, because Austin College, you were getting 1,800, which was a big salary.
And he raised you then to 2,000 after a year or two.
And because they had offers.
By the way, a properly raised and proper degree is from a proper institution, a man, whether a master's, but especially a PhD.
They do not go seeking positions.
Not in those days.
Nowadays, they do not only seek them, they scramble for them.
Because there are so many PhDs.
You don't.
We didn't do that in those days.
We waited for offers.
It's now a buyer's market.
Well, I don't know that it was that.
It is now, not then.
It was a feeling of dignity, the same as doctors do not advertise.
And we have a doctor friend up in Virginia who advertised.
with a picture taken of himself and wife and five children.
We know the wife particularly well up in Lynchburg, Virginia.
And that was put in the paper.
And the Medical Association sort of protested, because that might look as an advertisement.
And you know, or advertisement, I don't know which way you want to pronounce it.
We change in pronunciations, too, I think.
And for instance, you never see anything about the doctor or his practice.
The only thing you see is that doctor or doctor so-and-so are pleased to announce the association of so-and-so.
Or they may say location doctor so-and-so has moved his office or clinic
to such and such a place, which is for the convenience of people and not advertising.
And that's the way Ray never sought any place.
Of course, he went to Austin College because of the friendship of two family friends.
Do you remember what they were paying your professors in the department who worked for you or your instructors?
Do you remember what the salary scale was?
Here, I think we came to 2,400, and we thought that was enormous.
But, oh, it would be maybe 1,800 the way we left Austin College.
But it was plenty.
You know, you could buy much more.
Right in my head, the cigar got about 2,000.
Uh-huh.
And he was the one that was here.
I signed many pills, but I can't remember now what was on them.
No, or what you offered those who came
after you, the only thing, the only way you could get that would be to ask, um, ask, um...
Probably have to go to the comptroller.
No, you could, yes, the comptroller probably would know from the records, but he'd have to look pretty far back.
But you could ask the, um, Horace Bassett, I'm sure he'd be glad to tell you.
Okay.
And I think you could ask, um,
Al B. Nelson, who lived out college way out.
He came here about 35 or 36, I think, didn't he?
Hard to remember.
Wait a minute now.
This would be something like that.
The Fullers came seven years after.
The Fullers and Dean.
Who succeeded Dean?
Not Della Plain.
Who was before that?
Brooks.
That was seven years after we came.
They came, and that's when J.D.P.
Fuller came, who later went to the VMI, Virginia Military.
Let me think.
I can't remember what you offered him or what he came for, but that was seven years after we came.
And I remember telling Mrs. Brooks, he came in seven years after we came.
I remember that particularly by something I said.
I said, Mrs. Brooks, you know, if you stay here, there's a bug that bites you.
And she said, what's that?
I said, well, it's a bug that makes you want to stay here.
And if you stay here seven years, you will be absolutely captured by that bug.
And she said, how long have you been here?
I said, seven years.
So I remember that they came then.
He was mayor of Waco when he came.
So that's seven years.
That was in 1932 then.
You see, that's pretty far back.
And he was mayor of Waco.
And was he a professor?
Yes, he was a professor.
He was Dr. Brooks.
He was a professor in school and college administration.
And that's what Dean Friley took up in Chicago.
And we spent part of the summer up in Chicago at a friend's home who was going to be gone.
We went to the seaside for the children.
Lake Michigan, and they all got earrings.
And they were bathing in Lake Michigan.
And he went up there to, that was Dean Friley.
He went up there to get a degree.
I think he had a doctor's degree, but maybe he just went up there with that doctor's degree.
He was the one that wanted doctors here in this, because there were so few.
There was Humbert, and Sylvie, and Milsing, and Sonny.
And it seems to me there were six PhDs at the time that we came.
But it may have been 10.
I can't remember, because that surprised me.
That's one of the surprises.
Well, I think you've sort of picked our brains thoroughly.
I don't know if there's any brains left now.
was positioned to care of the boys.
They are cadets.
We used to call them cadets, or the boys.
And in fact, I think we said the boys more than anything else.
He was allowed on the side some life.
I remember one woman here, their young son, who was Jimmy Cashin, he was just a little fellow.
And he was born right here on the campus.
And they would ask him just to get him to make us laugh, though he didn't know why it was funny.
They'd say, what do the boys say?
Notice the word boys.
And he would say, rah, rah, rah, rah, rah, rah, rah, rah, rah, rah, like that.
So you see, we called it boys.
And they lived near Dr. Marsh, who was college physician when we came.
And I think he came perhaps the same year as he has a son who is James.
Jack Marsh, a physician, but Dr. Marsh has died.
He looked after the cadets or the boys and was really a specialist in respiratory diseases, which was the commonplace thing here, though he did operate minor things like appendicitis and so on.
And I think one Houston friend told me that this was called the appendicitis belt.
That didn't mean just the college, but it meant the town too.
And so a good many went for specialties, went to Houston, as we did.
We had no pediatrician.
and no ophthalmologist.
In fact, Dr. Rolstrom was the first ophthalmologist down in Beague, Houston, which was Beague even then.
So we would go down there, and others would go there.
They would take their children down to checkups if they were worried in any way.
And I think where they went to, oh, I can't remember the name.
We took our son there, both of them.
for a checkup, and everything was all right.
And we took for eyes.
You see, we were great readers.
And we had a nearsighted son, and a son who was operated on his eyes.
So we had to go to Houston for things like that.
And that's all I think we went to.
There were other specialists, but we didn't need specialists.
And people went to Temple for medical, Scott and White.
And some went up here to right north of us,
Marlin, I believe there's a clinic up there.
And Temple, though, was Dr. Marsh's recommendation.
I remember Ray went out to Temple.
I don't remember that.
Oh, Ray, that was in 29, because of when your father was sick.
Dr. Marsh recommended a general checkup up at Scott and White.
So you see, we just had to go away for special things.
And Dr. Marsh was a very kindly, friendly, would tell you things, and very likable, very likable.
He was also his widow.
And Jack was a nice kid.
Jack went on a trip to Europe.
when Sam Ray was a political officer in the State Department.
And when they had free time, he took off time to go to see Sam Ray up there.
And Mrs. Marsh told me that Jack said that, oh, Sam Ray, he is important.
And I said, no, he isn't.
He's just progressed, but I wouldn't say that it was topped.
But it seemed so, because he had crimson satin walls, you see, and could look over.
The embassy was a beautiful, restored palace, the Pallas Margarita, I think it was, in Rome.
And I said to Mrs. Marsh, but she was so kind to tell me that.
And I said, no, he's not important.
He's not important to his friend.
Oh, no, she says, but I'm in the department.
I shouldn't put that in.
I hope that is the number.
It's great.
Given credit.
If you're given credit, you see.
I couldn't choose.
I wanted to, because Johns Hopkins has a copyright on .
Oh, no, he wasn't making money.
It would also depend on how old the copyright is, too.
I think you've got, what, 27 years?
Is about all that thing's good for?
No, he had 1932.
Because Hopkins would have let him know.
But Samurai is his own.
He published it his own self.
I don't know how.
And I don't remember his name or anything.
you see, because it's John Patchett, William Patchett.
He makes that much off of it?
No, it sells for $13 a volume.
You get a nice percentage of that.
That's capital gains.
Yes, ma'am, it is.
But capital gains is better than real income because you pay only half of what your capital, you pay only half of what your capital gain is with.
I've gone through some of that last year for the 72 things we had.
